  <section class="bg-gray-50 py-16"><div class="section max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-8 text-center">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What fire safety services are required for commercial buildings in St. Paul, MN?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">St. Paul enforces the Minnesota State Fire Code / International Fire Code (IFC). Requirements include fire extinguishers (NFPA 10), fire alarms (NFPA 72), sprinklers (NFPA 13/25), and kitchen suppression for commercial cooking (NFPA 96). Minnesota enforces the IFC with state amendments through the State Fire Marshal Division.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often are fire inspections required in St. Paul?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The Saint Paul Fire Department conducts annual commercial property inspections. Fire extinguishers: monthly visual checks and annual professional inspection. Fire alarms: annual testing. Sprinklers: quarterly, semi-annual, and annual inspections. Kitchen suppression: semi-annual per NFPA 96.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Do I need special sprinkler systems for St. Paul's cold winters?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. Wet pipe sprinkler systems will freeze in any unheated space in St. Paul — including attics, parking garages, loading docks, and vestibules. These areas require dry pipe systems, anti-freeze systems, or electric heat tracing per NFPA 13. Minnesota's fire code is particularly attentive to cold-weather system failures. Have a licensed fire protection engineer specify the correct system for each space in your building.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Do restaurants in St. Paul need special fire suppression systems?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. All commercial cooking producing grease-laden vapors requires a wet chemical suppression system per NFPA 96, plus a Class K extinguisher within 30 feet of cooking equipment. Systems must be inspected semi-annually by a licensed technician.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who enforces fire codes in St. Paul, MN?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The Saint Paul Fire Department enforces fire codes within St. Paul city limits. The Minnesota State Fire Marshal Division licenses fire protection contractors statewide at (651) 201-7200.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>
